\begin_layout Section
Location and Scale Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a random variable (think of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 as a return, but it could be any random variable) with location parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

.
 The probability distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{R}(r)$
\end_inset

 and density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{R}(r)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 have the forms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F_{R}(r) & =F\left(\frac{r\,-\,\mu}{s}\right),\label{eq:LocScaleDistribution}\\[0.5em]
f_{R}(r) & =\frac{1}{s}f\left(\frac{r\,-\,\mu}{s}\right).\label{eq:LocScaleDensity}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Roughly speaking, the location parameter tells us where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{R}(r)$
\end_inset

 is centered, while the scale parameter tells us how widely it spreads.
 The most famous member of the location–scale family of distributions is
 the Normal distribution, whose density function is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{R}(r)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^{2}}}\exp\left(-\frac{\left(r-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right),\ -\infty<r<\infty.\label{eq:NormalDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mapping from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NormalDensity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LocScaleDensity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is obvious: the location parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the mean of the distribution, and the scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the square root of its variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A closely related location-scale family is the family of t-distributions,
 with density function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{R}(r)=\frac{\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu\,+\,1}{2}\right)}{\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)\sqrt{\pi\,\nu\,\tau^{2}}}\left(1+\frac{1}{\nu}\,\frac{\left(r-\mu\right)^{2}}{\tau^{2}}\right)^{\nicefrac{\left(\nu+1\right)}{2}},\ -\infty<r<\infty.\label{eq:tDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

location parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, and scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu>1$
\end_inset

, the mean of the distribution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu>2$
\end_inset

, its variance is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{2}\cdot\nicefrac{\nu}{\nu\,-\,2}$
\end_inset

.
 The mean of the t-distribution is undefined for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=1,$
\end_inset

 and its variance is undefined for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\leqslant2$
\end_inset

.
 In the special case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=1$
\end_inset

, the t-distribution is known as a Cauchy distribution, and its mean is
 undefined, even though the distribution is centered at 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A less well-known, but still important, member of the location-scale family
 is the Laplacian, or two-sided exponential, distribution with density function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{R}(r)=\frac{1}{2b}\exp\left(-\frac{\left|r-\mu\right|}{b}\right),\ -\infty<r<\infty.\label{eq:LaplacianDensity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The location parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the mean of the distribution, and the scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 times its standard deviation, or the square root of its variance.
 The Laplacian distribution can be shown to be a lateral translation by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 of the difference between two exponential random variables with pdf 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{\exp\left(\nicefrac{-r}{b}\right)}{\,b}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Most textbooks describe the exponential distribution in terms of a rate
 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 that is the reciprocal of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 We deliberately use 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 to emphasize the commonality with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LocScaleDensity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
