 latter the relation between scale and standard deviation, and the case
 (Cauchy) where the mean does not exist (except in a special sense) ** DONE
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Invariance Properties of Location, Scale, Covariance and Correlation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Mean and Standard Deviation Equivariance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{R}=\mathrm{E\left[\mathit{R}\right]}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{R}=\sqrt{\mathrm{var}(R)}$
\end_inset

 be the mean and standard deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{R}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\emph on
affine transformation
\emph default

\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An affine transformation has both a constant and a linear term – it is best
 thought of as a parallel shift of a linear transformation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{R}=a\,+\,bR
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a location parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

 is a scale parameter.
 It is straightforward to show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{\dot{R}} & =a\,+\,b\mu_{R}\\
\sigma_{\dot{R}} & =b\,\cdot\,\sigma_{R}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The first equation above shows that the mean is 
\emph on
location and scale equivariant
\emph default
, and the second equation shows that the standard deviation is 
\emph on
location invariant
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
scale equivariant
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Covariance Translation Invariance and Scale Equivariance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

 have covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cov}(r_{i},\,r_{j})$
\end_inset

 and assume that variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

 by the affine transformations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{r}_{i} & =a\,+\,b\,\cdot\,r_{i}\nonumber \\
\dot{r}_{j} & =c\,+\,d\,\cdot\,r_{j}.\label{eq:affineTF}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The resulting covariance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cov}(\dot{r}_{i},\,\dot{r}_{j})$
\end_inset

, of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{cov}(\dot{r}_{i},\,\dot{r}_{j})=b\,\cdot\,d\,\cdot\,\mathrm{cov}(r_{i},\,r_{j}),\label{eq:covAffineTF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and we describe this behavior by saying that covariances are 
\emph on
translation invariant
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
scale equivariant
\emph default
.

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Correlation Affine Invariance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the correlation of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{cor}(r_{i},\,r_{j})=\frac{\mathrm{cov}(r_{i},\,r_{j})}{\sigma_{r_{i}}\,\cdot\,\sigma_{r_{j}}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

it follows that follows that the correlation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{r}_{j}$
\end_inset

 obtained by the affine transform 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:affineTF"

\end_inset

 is the same as the correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{cor}(\dot{r}_{i},\,\dot{r}_{j})=\mathrm{cor}(r_{i},\,r_{j})\label{eq:corrsAffineInvariance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and we see that 
\emph on
correlations are affine invariant
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Corresponding Properties of Sample Estimators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to check that the above equivariance and invariance properties
 also hold for the sample based estimators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linearity of Covariances
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: covarianceLinearity"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have two random variables, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}\,y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathrm{cov}(x,\,z) & = & \mathrm{cov}\left(x,\ \sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}\,y_{i}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \mathrm{E}\left[\left(x\,-\,\mathrm{E\left[\mathit{x}\right]}\right)\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}y_{i}\,-\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}\,\mathrm{E}\left[y_{i}\right]\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \mathrm{E}\left[\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}\left(x\,-\,\mathrm{E}\left[x\right]\right)\left(y_{i}\,-\,\mathrm{E}\left[y_{i}\right]\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}\,\mathrm{E}\left[\left(x\,-\,\mathrm{E}\left[x\right]\right)\left(y_{i}\,-\,\mathrm{E}\left[y_{i}\right]\right)\right]\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}\,\mathrm{cov}(x,\,y_{i})\nonumber \\
 & = & \mathbf{a^{\prime}}\mathrm{cov}(x,\,\mathbf{y})\label{eq: covLinearity}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cov}(x,\,\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

–dimensional column vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 element 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cov}(x,\,y_{i})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A leading application of the above covariance linearity property is the
 computation of the covariance between the return of a portfolio, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{P}$
\end_inset

, and its 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 constituent asset, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{P} & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}w_{i}\,r_{i}=\mathbf{w}^{\prime}\mathbf{r},\label{eq:PortReturn}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and application of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: covLinearity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{cov}(r_{i},\,r_{P}) & =\sum_{j=1}^{n}w_{j}\,\mathrm{cov}(r_{i},\,r_{j})\nonumber \\
 & =\mathbf{w}^{\prime}\mathrm{cov}(r_{i},\,\mathbf{r}).\label{eq: covAssetWithPortfolio}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimator Bias, Variance and Mean Squared Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A considerable amount of the quantitative finance literature is written
 primarily from a mathematical point of view, e.g., as in much of the earlier
 sections of this chapter.
 But as was made evident already in the second section of this chapter on
 risk estimators, a mathematical model formula by itself is not enough,
 one must use data to estimate the parameter or parameters of a mathematical
 model.
 Also, the factor models discussed in the previous section beg for some
 discussion of how the parameters of single–factor and multi–factor models
 are estimated from observed data, and what the basic properties are of
 the estimators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this section we describe what we regard as the main classical principles
 of parameter estimation that apply to estimators of simple one–dimensional
 parameters such as the mean and volatility of returns, the correlation
 of a pair of returns, and also apply to the estimates of each of the components
 of a vector of multi–factor model coefficients, and each of the pairwise
 covariance estimators in a covariance matrix estimate.
\end_layout

\end_inset

In this section we focus on estimators of a scalar parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, whose value is unknown and is to be estimated using a set of random returns
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t},$
\end_inset

 collected over 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 time periods 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,\,2,\,\ldots,\,n$
\end_inset

.
 Using the vector notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, we denote the estimator as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}(\mathbf{r})=\hat{\theta}_{n}(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Since the estimator is a function of random returns, the estimator itself
 is a random variable whose basic properties are bias, variance, and mean
 squared error (MSE).

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unbiased versus Biased Estimators
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: estUnbiased"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\emph on
unbiased 
\emph default
estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is one for which the expected value of the estimator is equal to the unknown
 true parameter value 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\buTheta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\buTheta$
\end_inset

 is a parameter space.
 For example, in the case of a location parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\mu$
\end_inset

, the parameter space will usually be the set of all finite real numbers,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\buTheta=\left\{ x:-\infty<x<+\infty\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In the case of a variance parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, the parameter space will be the set all non–negative real numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\buTheta=\left\{ x:\,x\geqslant0\right\} $
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\rho$
\end_inset

 is a correlation coefficient, the parameter space is the set of all numbers
 less than or equal to one in magnitude, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\buTheta=\left\{ x:\,|x|\leqslant1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the mathematical expression for unbiased of an estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]=\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}(\mathbf{r})\right]=\theta,\ \forall\,\theta\in\uTheta.\label{eq: unbiased estimator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is straightforward to show that the sample mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{r}=\frac{1}{n}{\textstyle \sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}r_{t}}$
\end_inset

 is an unbiased estimator of the true mean (expected value) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the above equality does not hold, the estimator is 
\emph on
biased
\emph default
, and its bias is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)=\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\,-\,\theta,\,\forall\,\theta\in\uTheta.\label{eq: biasDefinition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example of a well–known, but slightly biased, estimator, consider
 the following sample variance estimator of an unknown true variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2}=\frac{1}{n}\,{\displaystyle \sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}}\left(r_{t}\,-\,\overline{r}\right)^{2}.\label{eq: sampleVarianceBiased}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is known that for independent and identically distributed 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 with finite variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, the sample variance estimator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{n}^{2}=\frac{1}{n\,-\,1}\,{\displaystyle \sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}}\left(r_{t}\,-\,\overline{r}\right)^{2}\label{eq: sampleVarianceUnbiased}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is unbiased, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[S_{n}^{2}\right]=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the expected value of the sample variance 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: sampleVarianceBiased"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2}\right]=\mathrm{E}\left[\frac{1}{n}\,{\displaystyle \sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}}\left(r_{t}-\overline{r}\right)^{2}\right]=\frac{n\,-\,1}{n}\,\mathrm{E}\left[S_{n}^{2}\right]=\frac{n\,-\,1}{n}\,\sigma^{2}\label{eq: biasedSampleVariance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and it has a negative bias
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B\left(\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2}\right)=\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2}\right]\,-\,\sigma^{2}=-\frac{1}{n}\sigma^{2}\label{eq: biasOfBiasedSampleVariance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that goes to zero as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Portfolio managers will seldom be concerned about such bias, which for
 a sample of size 50 is no larger than 2%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Portfolio managers and investors generally pay little attention to returns
 variance, and instead focus on returns volatility, or returns standard
 deviation, and estimate it using the sample volatility estimator:
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{n}=\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\,{\displaystyle \sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}}\left(r_{t}\,-\,\overline{r}\right)^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This volatility estimator is biased, as is the estimator with the divisor
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

, even for normally distributed returns, but the bias can be shown to go
 to zero as the sample size tends to infinity.

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged
For normally distributed returns, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Holtzman1950"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AhnFessler2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 derive an unbiased estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, and some experimentation shows that for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geqslant4$
\end_inset

, an almost perfectly unbiased estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 can be obtained using the estimator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}_{n}=\sqrt{\frac{1}{n-1.5}\,{\displaystyle \sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}}\left(r_{t}\,-\,\overline{r}\right)^{2}}.\label{eq:AhnFesslerUnbiasedEstimateOfSigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Principle of Unbiasedness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If possible, one should use an estimator that is unbiased for every finite
 sample size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 However, this often not possible, and one should then whenever possible
 use a 
\emph on
consistent
\emph default
 estimator, for which the finite sample bias goes to zero as the sample
 size tends to infinity.
 In the context of robust estimation, it may not be possible to obtain a
 consistent estimator, and this is discussed further in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec: estAsympVariance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimator Mean Squared Error
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: estMSE"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mean squared error (MSE) of an estimator of a scalar quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}=\hat{\theta}_{n}(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{MSE}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)=\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\theta\right)^{2}\right]\label{eq:MSEscalar}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we emphasize that the expected value depends implicitly on the distributio
n of the data 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n}$
\end_inset

, The right hand side of the above equation may be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\theta\right)^{2}\right] & =\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\,+\,\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\,-\,\theta\right)^{2}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\right)^{2}\right]\,+\,\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\,-\,\theta\right)^{2}\right]\,+\,\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\right)\left(\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\,-\,\theta\right)\right].\label{eq:MSEexpanded}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term above is the variance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

, of the estimator, and the second term is the square of the bias 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)=\mathrm{E}\left[\hat{\theta}_{n}\right]\,-\,\theta$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to show that the last term on the right hand side above is zero,
 giving us the variance plus squared bias decomposition of MSE:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{MSE}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)=\mathrm{var}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)\,+\,B^{2}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right).\label{eq: mseDecomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three important things to remember about MSE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For an unbiased estimator, the estimator MSE error is equal to its variance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For a biased estimator, one needs to be concerned about the squared bias
 contribution to MSE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Estimators can be applied to vector-valued quantities (e.g.
 a vector with the returns of all securities in the S&P 500) as well as
 to scalars: the 
\begin_inset Formula $MSE$
\end_inset

 of an estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\buTheta}_{n}=\hat{\buTheta}_{n}(\mathbf{r}_{1},\,\mathbf{r}_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,\mathbf{r}_{n})$
\end_inset

 is the sum of the MSE's of its individual components, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{MSE}\left(\hat{\buTheta}_{n}\right) & =\mathrm{E}\left[\left\Vert \hat{\buTheta}_{n}\,-\,\buTheta\right\Vert ^{2}\right].\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i}\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\hat{\buTheta}_{i,\,n}\,-\,\buTheta_{i}\right)^{2}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i}\mathrm{var}\left(\hat{\buTheta}_{i,\,n}\right)\,+\,B^{2}\left(\buTheta_{i}\right)\label{eq:MSEvector}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Later, we will see that the Minimum MSE estimator is unbiased for a scalar
 parameter.
 The most commonly used estimators for a vector of parameters, including
 the sample mean, Ordinary Least Squares and sample covariance matrices,
 are also either unbiased or have biases of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{N}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of parameters being estimated.
 But when estimating a vector of parameters, it is sometimes possible to
 admit a little bias in exchange for a much lower variance, so that the
 Minimum MSE estimator is slightly biased.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This remarkable result, due to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Stein1956"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, is counterintuitive: it is not easily proved or digested, and we refer
 the interested reader to the non-technical exposition in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "EfronMorris1977"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as well as to the advanced treatment in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TsukumaKubokawa2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 It also lies at the heart of asymptotic robust regression theory (see Section
 5.8 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "YohaiZamar1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Svarc2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), where the primary objective is to control the bias in parameter estimates
 under mixture models.
 
\end_layout

