\begin_layout Subsection
Generalized Least Squares
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Generalized Least Squares
\emph default
 (GLS) combines two important ideas to identify an optimal set of coefficients
 for the linear regression model when its errors are correlated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Individual observations can be weighted in inverse proportion to the variance
 of their residuals to equalize their relative importance (the same idea
 was earlier applied in our discussion of Weighted Least Squares), and
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The distance between a vector of correlated residuals and the mean of their
 joint distribution can be computed using a scale invariant distance measure
 known as the 
\emph on
Mahalanobis distance
\emph default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix A for a discussion of the Mahalanobis distance.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, the GLS fit is the solution to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{GLS}=\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\,\bubeta\right)^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}^{-1}}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\,\bubeta\right),\label{eq:GLSbeta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is the known, non–singular, covariance matrix of the errors.
 Replacing our diagonal weight matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{W}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 simultaneously scales and decorrelates the errors, and equalizes the relative
 importance of each term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GLSbeta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}^{-1}}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}$
\end_inset

 is invertible, the GLS coefficients are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{GLS}=\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}^{-1}\,}\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)^{-1}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{C}^{-1}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}.\label{eq:GLSbeta1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is square, symmetric, and positive definite, it can be factored as
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See the discussion of the Singular Value Decomposition in Appendix A,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{C}^{-1}=\buOmega^{\prime}\,\buOmega,\label{eq:CinverseDecomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and we can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GLSbeta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\bubeta}_{GLS} & =\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(\left(\mathbf{\buOmega\,}\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\right)\,-\,\left(\mathbf{\buOmega\,}\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)\,\bubeta\right)^{\prime}\,\left(\left(\mathbf{\buOmega}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\right)-\left(\mathbf{\buOmega}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)\,\bubeta\right),\label{eq:GLSBeta2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

illuminating the fact that GLS is just the application of OLS to a particular
 transformation of the raw data
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Chapter 1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hayashi2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

