\begin_layout Subsection
Least Squares Inference with Normally Distributed Errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some special cases, OLS yields information about the distribution of
 the regression coefficients, allowing us to test hypotheses about their
 value.
 In particular, if the errors have an i.i.d.
 normal distribution, i.e., if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bueps\,|\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\,\sim\,\mathrm{MVN}\left(0,\ \sigma^{2}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}\right)\ \forall\,\mathbf{X},\label{eq:MultivariateNormalErrors}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the sampling distribution of the regression coefficients is also multivariate
 normal, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\bubeta}_{OLS}\,\mathrm{-\,}\bubeta & =\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)^{-1}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\,\mathrm{-\,}\bubeta\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)^{-1}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\,\bubeta\,+\,\bueps\right)\,\mathrm{-\,}\bubeta\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)^{-1}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\bueps.\label{eq:BetaRelatesToEpsilon}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that the covariance matrix of the sampling errors of the regression
 coefficients is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Cov\left(\hat{\bubeta}_{OLS}\,|\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)\sim\mathrm{MVN}\left(0,\ \sigma^{2}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)^{-1}\right).\label{eq:MultivariateNormalSamplingErrors}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Even though 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is unknown, we can obtain an unbiased estimate of it using the squared
 residuals 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The denominator of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sSquared"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n\,-\,m\,-\,1$
\end_inset

, and not 
\begin_inset Formula $n\,-\,m$
\end_inset

, because we have a total of 
\begin_inset Formula $m\,+\,1$
\end_inset

 explanatory variables: an intercept and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 predictor variables.
 In some textbooks, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be the intercept, which reduces the number of explanatory
 variables to 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and makes the denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $n\,-\,m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{2}=\frac{\hat{\bueps}^{\prime}\ \hat{\bueps}}{n\,-\,m\,-\,1},\label{eq:sSquared}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

using which the standard error of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 regression coefficient can be computed as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SE\left(\hat{\beta}_{j,\,OLS}\right)=\sqrt{s^{2}\,\times\,\left(\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\right)^{-1}\right)_{j,\,j}}\,,\ 1\leqslant j\leqslant m+1.\label{eq:SEofBetaj}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we have a hypothesized value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{j}$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\beta_{j}}$
\end_inset

, we can test the hypothesis
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{0}:\ \beta_{j}=\overline{\beta_{j}}\label{eq:NullHypothesis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

using the t–test, whose t–statistic
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{j}=\frac{\hat{\beta}_{j,\,OLS}\,-\,\overline{\beta_{j}}}{SE\left(\hat{\beta}_{j,\,OLS}\right)},\label{eq:tStatRegression}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

has a 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\,-\,m\,-\,1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we specify a two–sided significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, we can reject the null hypothesis if the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

–statistic is sufficiently large, i.e., if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
|t_{j}|>t_{\alpha/2}\left(n\,-\,m\,-\,1\right).\label{eq:tTestRegression}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\beta_{j}}$
\end_inset

