reference "eq:MMSEPredictor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is true in general, it is not always easy to implement – 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{y\,|\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}}$
\end_inset

 is not usually known, and even if it is, it may be non–linear, time–varying,
 and computationally taxing.
 A widely used solution to these problems is to restrict 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 to be an affine function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

, and to write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{y}=\alpha\,+\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}^{\prime}\,\bubeta\label{eq:LinearMMSEAppB1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is the known observable and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

is a vector of unknown coefficients
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For clarity of exposition, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 reflects only the weights applied to the random variables – the constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is treated separately.
 In our earlier development of OLS, in contrast, our problem formulation
 was greatly simplified by making 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 the first entry in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

.

