\begin_layout Subsection
Conditional Distribution of a Multivariate Normal Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the central role that the conditional mean plays in MMSE prediction
 of scalar random variables, it is natural to ask if one can compute the
 conditional mean of a random vector.
 In many cases of interest, we can.
 Let
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}\\
\hline \mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:MultivariateNormal1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

be a vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}+n_{2}$
\end_inset

 elements that is partitioned into two sub–vectors: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}$
\end_inset

, the upper portion, has 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 elements, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}$
\end_inset

, the lower part, has 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

 elements.
 The distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is assumed to have a mean vector and covariance matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bumu & =\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bumu_{1}\\
\hline \bumu_{2}
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:MultivariateNormalMu}\\[0.5em]
\mathbf{\Sigma} & =\left[\begin{array}{c|c}
\mathrm{\mathbf{\Sigma}_{11}}\, & \,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}\\
\hline \mathbf{\Sigma}_{21}\, & \,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{22}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:MultivariateNormalSigma}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dimensions of the partitioned vector and matrix must be consistent with
 the dimensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In the special case when the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is multivariate normal with mean vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\bumu$
\end_inset

 and covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}$
\end_inset

, its pdf is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(\mathbf{x}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\left(2\pi\right)^{n_{1}\,+\,n_{2}}det\left(\mathbf{\Sigma}\right)}}\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\,-\,\bumu\right)\,\mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\,-\,\bumu\right)\right).\label{eq:MultivariateNormalDistribution1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unconditional distributions of both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are also multivariate normal, and their pdfs are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(\mathbf{x}_{1}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\left(2\pi\right)^{n_{1}}det\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{\Sigma}_{11}}\right)}}\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}\,-\,\bumu_{1}\right)\mathrm{\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{11}^{-1}}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}\,-\,\bumu_{1}\right)\right)\label{eq:MultivariateNormalDistribution2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(\mathbf{x}_{2}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\left(2\pi\right)^{n_{2}}det\left(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{22}\right)}}\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}\,-\,\bumu_{2}\right)\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{22}^{-1}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}\,-\,\bumu_{2}\right)\right),\label{eq:MultivariateNormalDistribution3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 conditioned on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is multivariate normal with a conditional mean vector and covariance matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bumu_{2\,|\,1} & =\bumu_{2}\,+\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{21}\mathrm{\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{11}^{-1}}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{1}\,-\,\bumu_{1}\right)\label{eq:ConditionalMean}\\[0.5em]
\mathbf{\Sigma}_{2\,|\,1} & =\mathbf{\Sigma}_{22}\,-\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{21}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{\Sigma}_{11}^{-1}}\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}.\label{eq:ConditionalCovMat}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditional distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 can also be derived using the fact that it is the ratio of the joint distributi
on of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 (i.e., the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

) to the marginal distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{2\,|\,1}\left(\mathbf{x}_{2}\right)=\frac{f\left(\mathbf{x}\right)}{f\left(\mathbf{x}_{1}\right)},\label{eq:MarginalDistributionX2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and can be shown to be
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An accessible derivation of this result can be found at 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/30588/deriving-the-conditional-distribut
ions-of-a-multivariate-normal-distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as well as in Section 3.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MardiaKentBibby"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{2\,|\,1}\left(\mathbf{x}_{2}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\left(2\pi\right)^{n_{2}}det\left(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{2\,|\,1}\right)}}\exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}\,-\,\bumu_{2\,|\,1}\right)\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{2\,1}^{-1}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{2}\,-\,\bumu_{2\,|\,1}\right)\right).\label{eq:MultivariateNormalDistribution4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In fact, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConditionalMean"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is remarkably general: it gives the conditional mean
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unfortunately, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConditionalCovMat"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 does not correspondingly give the conditional covariance matrix for all
 elliptical distribtions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for all elliptical distributions with finite means, such as the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 distribution with 2 or more degrees of freedom.
 The proof of this result is complex, and we refer the interested reader
 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CambanisHuangSimons1981"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ding2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimators via the Plug-In Principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
plug–in
\emph default
 
\emph on
principle
\emph default
 provides a way to obtain a non–parametric estimator of a parameter or other
 quantity from the true but unknown value of the parameter or other quantity
 as described in terms of an integral with respect to a probability density
 or distribution function.
 This principle is nicely described in Chapter 4 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "EfronTibshirani1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and we provide a brief description of it here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The true but unknown value of a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 for a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 with probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $f(r)$
\end_inset

 and distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(r)$
\end_inset

 can be written in the functional form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta(F)=\int g(r;\,F)\,dF(r)=\int g(r;\,F)\,f(r)\,dr\label{eq:parameterFunctional}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some appropriate function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)$
\end_inset

.
 For example, by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r;\,F)=r$
\end_inset

, the mean of the distribution may be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu(F)=\int r\,dF(r)\label{eq:meanFunctional}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and by choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r;\,F)=(r\,-\,\mu(F))^{2}$
\end_inset

, the variance can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma^{2}(F)=\int(r\,-\,\mu(F))^{2}\,dF(r).\label{eq:varianceFunctional}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The standard deviation functional, is of course, just
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma(F)=\sqrt{\int(r\,-\,\mu(F))^{2}\,dF(r)}.\label{eq:stdDevFunctional}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the functional representation of a parameter we can obtain a parameter
 estimator by substituting the empirical distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 for the true, but unknown, distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The empirical distribution function (e.d.f.) is a discrete probability function
 that assigns a probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n$
\end_inset

 to each of the observed values 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots,\,r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 So for the general case we have the plug–in estimator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\theta} & =\theta(F_{n})\nonumber \\
 & =\int g(r;\,F_{n})\,dF_{n}(r)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}g(r_{i};\,F_{n})\,P(r=r_{i})\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}g(r_{i};\,F_{n}).\label{eq:pluginEstimator}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Applying the plug–in principle to the mean functional gives the sample mean
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mu}=\bar{r}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}r_{i},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and applying it to the variance functional gives the sample variance
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\sigma}^{2}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}(r_{t}\,-\,\bar{r})^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Maximum Likelihood Estimators 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: MLEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we begin by discussing maximum–likelihood estimators (MLEs)
 of location and scale parameters, then extend the discussion to the case
 of linear regression model coefficient estimators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
** I still need to reorganize and smooth out this Section.
 Doug 02/16/2020 **
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Location and Scale MLEs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:LocationandScaleMLEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume we have 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 i.i.d.
 observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})$
\end_inset

 of a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 whose pdf is drawn from the location–scale family.
 The returns can be be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{i}=\mu\,+\,s\,\cdot\,\epsilon_{i},\quad i=1,\,2,\,\ldots\,,\,n.\label{eq: locScaleModReturns}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The pdf of each of observation is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LocScaleDensity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and their joint pdf 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{r};\,\mu,\,s)$
\end_inset

 is the product of their densities.
 The 
\emph on
likelihood function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\mu,\,s)$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the joint density function of the observations, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 fixed at the observed data values and with 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 variable, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L(\mu,\,s)=\prod_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\frac{1}{s}f\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right).\label{eq:LikelihoodLocScale}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is common practice in theoretical statistics to focus instead on the
 log–likelihood function 
\begin_inset Formula $l(\mu,\,s)$
\end_inset

, defined using the natural logarithm, as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
l(\mu,\,s) & =\ln\,L(\mu,\,s)\nonumber \\
 & =\ln\left(\prod_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\frac{1}{s}f\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =-N\,\cdot\,\ln(s)\,+\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\ln f\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right).\label{eq:LogLikelihoodLocScale}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The maximum likelihood estimates, or MLE's, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{\mu},\,\hat{s})_{mle}$
\end_inset

 are the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 that maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $l(\mu,\,s)$
\end_inset

 and thus maximize the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 being observed:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\hat{\mu},\,\hat{s})_{mle}=\underset{\mu,\,s}{\mathrm{argmax}}\left(-N\cdot\ln(s)\,+\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\ln f\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right)\right).\label{eq:JointMLEmuSigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When estimating 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 as fixed so that we can ignore the first term in the bracket, and the MLE
 problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:JointMLEmuSigma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mu}_{mle}=\underset{\mu}{\mathrm{argmax}}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\ln f\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right),\label{eq:locMLEmaxProblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which can (in principle at least) be solved by computing the partial derivative
 of the right hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:locMLEmaxProblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and equating the derivative to 0.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:JointMLEmuSigma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 usually represents a challenging non–convex numerical optimization problem,
 we can gain a useful understanding of the mechanics of maximum likelihood
 estimation by acting as if 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is known, and maximizing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:JointMLEmuSigma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 In this case we can ignore 
\begin_inset Formula $N\cdot\ln(s)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: regJointMLE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and minimize the negative of the second term:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mu}_{mle}=\underset{\mu}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(-\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\ln f\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right)\right).\label{eq:MLEsknown}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=-\ln\,f(x)$
\end_inset

 to be a 
\emph on
loss function
\emph default
, the above MLE can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mu}_{mle}=\underset{\mu}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\rho\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right)\right),\label{eq: MLEasLossFunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which expresses the MLE of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 as the value that minimizes a sum of loss functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we differentiate the right hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: MLEasLossFunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and equate the result to 0, we obtain the estimating equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\psi\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mu}{s}\right)=0,\label{eq: MLEestEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It is easily seen that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\psi(x) & =\frac{d}{dx}\rho(x)\nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{d}{dx}\ln\,f(x)\nonumber \\
 & =-\dfrac{f^{\prime}(x)}{f(x)}.\label{eq: scoreFunction}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
More generally, when the distribution is characterized by more than one
 parameter, it is the 
\emph on
gradient
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is known as the 
\emph on
score function
\emph default
 in mathematical statistics, and measures the sensitivity of the likelilihood
 to small changes in the estimated parameter.
 It attains a value of 0 at a local minimum of the loss function, allowing
 the identification of the parameter value that maximizes the likelihood
 function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now discuss two important distributions that admit simple solutions to
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: MLEestEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and a third one which does not, but is none the less an important distribution
 for modeling fat–tailed asset returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Normal Distribution MLE.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:NormalDistributionMLE."

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In the case of the standard normal pdf we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}exp\left(-x^{2}\,/\,2\right)\label{eq:StandardNormalPdf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{mle,\,normal}(x)=\ln(2\pi)\,/\,2\,+\,x^{2}\,/\,2\label{eq:rhoStandardNormal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{mle,\,normal}(x)=x.\label{eq:psiNormalMLE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: MLEestEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reduces to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}r_{i} & =N\cdot\hat{\mu}_{mle,\,normal},\label{eq:NormalMLEsolution}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and the location estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{mle,\,normal}$
\end_inset

 is seen to be the sample mean.
 Likewise, the joint estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{mle,\,normal}$
\end_inset

 can be shown to be the sample standard deviation obtained as the square
 root of the biased sample variance 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: biasedSampleVariance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Laplacian Distribution MLE.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:LaplacianDistributionMLE."

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The standard form of the Laplacian (symmetric two–sided exponential) distributio
n is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x)=\frac{1}{2}\,\cdot\,exp\left(-\mid x\mid\right),\label{eq:StandardLaplacianPdf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{mle,\,Laplacian}(x)=constant\,+\,\mid x\mid,\label{eq:rhoStandardLaplacian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{mle,\,Laplacian}(x)=sgn(x)=\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
+1,\quad x>0\\
\ \,0,\quad x=0\\
-1,\quad x<0
\end{array}\right..\label{eq: sgnFunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again, the location MLE does not depend upon 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: sgnFunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 makes clear that the optimal estimate of location must have the same number
 of observations to its left as it does to its right, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{mle,\,Laplacian}=MED(\mathbf{r}).$
\end_inset

 It is easily shown that the median is unique for an odd sample size, and
 is not unique for an even sample size.
 By convention, it is taken to be the mean of the two middle observations
 when the sample size is even.
 It can also be shown that the scale MLE is the mean–absolute deviation
 about the median estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{mle,\,Laplacian}=n^{-1}\cdot\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}|r_{i}\,-\,MED(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

|.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
t–Distribution MLE
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:tDistributionMLE"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In this case we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the standard t–distribution pdf with a known degrees of freedom parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, and have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x)=\dfrac{\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu\,+\,1}{2}\right)}{\sqrt{2\pi}\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)}\left(1\,+\,x^{2}/\nu\right)^{-(\nu\,+\,1)/2}.\label{eq:StandardTpdf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{mle,\,tdist}(x)=constant\,+\,\frac{\nu\,+\,1}{2}log\left(1\,+\,x^{2}/\nu\right)\label{eq:rhoStandardT}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{mle,\,tdist}(x)=\frac{\nu\,+\,1}{\nu}\frac{x}{1\,+\,x^{2}/\nu}.\label{eq:psiStandardT}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is a non–convex optimization problem that requires a good numerical
 optimization algorithm, as well as an initial estimate of location and
 knowledge of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, both of which may have to be estimated from data.
 Consequently, even though the t–distribution has often been proposed for
 modeling fat–tailed distributions that are not well modeled by a Laplacian
 distribution, its MLE has not seen wide usage, though good numerical algorithms
 to solve the MLE are found in packages such as 
\family typewriter
sn
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
MASS, both of which
\family default
 are described in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
FatTailedDistributionSection
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: mleRhoPsiPlots"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 displays the loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and score functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 for these three examples.
 In the case of the t–distributions, the scale parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is set so that the standard deviation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=1$
\end_inset

, using the known relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=s^{2}\cdot\nu/(\nu\,-\,2)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

