\begin_layout Subsection
Regression Model MLEs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:RegressionModelMLEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next extend our results on MLEs to cross–section regression models.
 We focus on the cross–section model for a single time period with the time
 subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 dropped, but keep in mind that the model will be fit for each time period
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in some time window:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r_{i} & =f_{o}\,+\,\beta_{i1}\,\cdot\,f_{1}\,+\,\beta_{i2}\,\cdot\,f_{2}\,+\,\cdots\,+\,\beta_{iK}\,\cdot\,f_{K}\,+\,\varepsilon_{i},\ i=1,\,2,\,\cdots\,,\,N.\label{eq: linRegModNoVectors}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times(K+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 row is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}=(1,\,\beta_{i1},\,\beta_{i2},\,\cdots\,,\beta_{iK})$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}=(f_{o},\,f_{1},\,\cdots\,,\,f_{K})^{\prime},$
\end_inset

 Then the above model may be written more compactly as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{i}=\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}\,+\,\varepsilon_{i},\ i=1,2,\cdots,N.\label{eq: linRegMod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above model the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{ik}$
\end_inset

 are fixed predictor variables and the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}$
\end_inset

 are unknown coefficients, and for this single time–period model the 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be considered as unknown regression coefficient parameters, with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{o}$
\end_inset

 being the intercept
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In practice, the cross–section factor models are fit for each time period
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and the resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k\,t}$
\end_inset

 are treated as random variables that define random time series as time
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 evolves.
 This aspect is discussed further in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
CrossSectionalFactorModelsChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We make the standard assumption that the errors 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) random variables that
 are also independent of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{ik}$
\end_inset

, and further assume that they have a pdf of the scale family form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(\epsilon)=\frac{1}{s}p_{0}\left(\frac{\epsilon}{s}\right),\ s>0\label{eq: pdfScaledEpsilon}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a standard symmetric density such as a standard normal or standard Laplacian
 distribution.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: linRegMod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(\epsilon_{i})=\frac{1}{s}p_{0}\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right),\label{eq: regObsPdf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and since the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 are i.i.d., the joint probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{r};\,\mathbf{f},\,s)$
\end_inset

 of the observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Should include the generalization to observation dependent scale 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

, and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 for the normal errors case.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f(\mathbf{r};\,\mathbf{f},\,s) & =\prod_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\frac{1}{s}p_{0}\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right).\label{eq: regJointObsPdf}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that the log–likelihood function, 
\begin_inset Formula $l(\mathbf{f},s)$
\end_inset

, is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
l(\mathbf{f},\,s) & =\ln\,L(\mathbf{f},\,s)\nonumber \\
 & =-N\,\cdot\,\ln(s)\,+\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\ln p_{0}\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right),\label{eq: regLogLikelihood}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is virtually identical to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:JointMLEmuSigma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum likelihood estimates 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{\mathbf{f}},\,\hat{s})_{mle}$
\end_inset

 are the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbf{f},\,s)$
\end_inset

 that maximize the above log–likelihood, and we write this as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(\hat{\mathbf{f}},\,\hat{s})_{mle}=\underset{\mathbf{f},\,s}{\mathrm{argmax}}\left(-N\cdot\ln(s)\,+\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\ln p_{0}\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right)\right).\label{eq: regJointMLE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again, we explore the impact of non–normal 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 on the linear regression MLE by acting as if 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is known, and consider the optimization only with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

.
 By analogy to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MLEsknown"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: MLEasLossFunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we can write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle}=\underset{\mathbf{f}}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(-\sum_{i=1}^{N}\ln p_{0}\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right)\right),\label{eq: regMLEsknown}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle}=\underset{\mathbf{f}}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{N}\rho\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right)\right),\label{eq: regMLEasLossMin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=-\ln\,p_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By taking the derivative of the right hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: regMLEasLossMin"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{f}$
\end_inset

, and setting it equal to zero, we can characterize 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle}$
\end_inset

 as the solution of the estimating equation
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{N}\mathbf{b}_{i}\psi\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right)=0\label{eq: regMLEestEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=\frac{d}{dx}\rho(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now discuss three possible error distribution choices in terms of the
 pdf 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

, and their corresponding regression estimators.

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Normal Distribution Regression MLE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In the case, the density 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the standard normal pdf, and as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: regMLEasLossMin"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 does not depend upon 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, the result is the least–squares (LS) estimate
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle,\,normal} & =\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{LS}=\underset{\mathbf{f}}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}(r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{f})^{2}\right),\label{eq: LSminimization}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: regMLEestEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 becomes the corresponding LS normal equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\mathbf{b}_{i}\left(r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\,\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{LS}\right)=\mathbf{0}.\label{eq: LSnormalEqns}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Laplacian Distribution Regression MLE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the Laplacian pdf, so that the resulting regression estimator is the
 Least–Absolute–Deviation (LAD) estimator:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle,\,Laplacian} & =\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{LAD}=\underset{\mathbf{f}}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}|r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}|\right).\label{eq: LADminimization}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The 
\emph on
LAD
\emph default
 estimator is also known as the 
\emph on
L1
\emph default
 estimator, and good numerical methods for solving the 
\emph on
LAD/L1
\emph default
 minimization problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: LADminimization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are widely available in both commercial and open source software packages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
t–Distribution Regression MLE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
In this case we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the standard t–distribution pdf with known parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, and the t–distribution regression MLE minimization problem becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle,\,tdist}=\underset{\mathbf{f}}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\log\left(1\,+\,\dfrac{1}{\nu}\left(\frac{r_{i}\,-\,\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\mathbf{f}}{s}\right)^{2}\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As in the case of Example 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "exa:tDistributionMLE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the above is a non–convex optimization problem that is not easily solved
 in closed form, though some of the powerful numerical solution techniques
 described in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
RobustMethodsChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "AzzaliniCapitanio2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have applicability to this problem as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Error Distribution Tail Fatness and Shapes of MLE Rho and Psi Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note the relationship between the fatness of the tail
 of the error distributions, and the shapes of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 functions.
 For the normal distributions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{mle,\,normal}(x)$
\end_inset

 is quadratic and grows very rapidly, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{mle,\,normal}(x)=x$
\end_inset

 is increasing and unbounded.
 For Laplacian distributions, which are more fat–tailed than normal distribution
s, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{mle,\,exp}(x)=|x|$
\end_inset

 grows only linearly but is unbounded, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{mle,\,exp}(x)=sgn(x)$
\end_inset

 is non–decreasing and bounded.
 For t–distributions, which are more fat–tailed than the Laplacian distribution,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{mle,\,tdist}(x)$
\end_inset

 grows only logarithmically (slower than linear) but is still unbounded,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{mle,\,tdist}(x)$
\end_inset

 is not only bounded but is also non–monotonic and decreases to zero as
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 tends to plus and minus infinity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Joint MLE of Regression and Scale Parameters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Computing the joint MLEs 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{mle}$
\end_inset

 of the regression and scale parameters is in general a complex nonlinear
 optimization for non–normal error distributions such as the t–distribution.
 However, in the case of the normal and Laplacian distributions, it is straightf
orward to derive formulas for the joint MLEs.
 For the normal distribution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{mle,\,normal}$
\end_inset

 is the square root of the sample average of the squared residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\epsilon}_{i}=r_{i}-\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle,\,normal}$
\end_inset

 .
 For Laplacian distributions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}_{mle,\,exp}$
\end_inset

 is the sample average of the absolute value of the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\epsilon}_{i}=r_{i}-\mathbf{b}_{i}^{\prime}\hat{\mathbf{f}}_{mle,\,normal}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The Maximum Likelihood Principle and Asymptotic Optimality of MLEs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This 
\emph on
maximum–likelihood principle
\emph default
 asserts that if one knows the data distribution then one should use a maximum–l
ikelihood estimator.
 Although this is only a reasonableness principle that is commonly invoked
 in the case of finite–sample estimators, it has the benefit of the following
 asymptotic optimality property: if the data is generated by an assumed
 distribution, then the MLE based on that distribution has an asymptotic
 variance that is the smallest asymptotic variance achievable by a consistent
 estimator.
 For a given distribution there is an analytic expression for that minimum
 variance, called the information–inequality lower bound.
 The formula for the lower bound is given in TS 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: Fisher Info & MLE Optimality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximum Likelihood Estimators generalize naturally to outlier–resistant
 robust estimators, and the similarities between the problem formulations
 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: MLEs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
RobustMethodsChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

are striking.
 In fact, a regression M-estimator is best viewed as an outlier-resistant
 generalization of the regression MLE equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: regMLEasLossMin"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: regMLEestEqn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Covariance Matrix MLEs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sample covariance matrix estimator 
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged
is known to be a maximum likelihood estimator when the return vectors 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf r}_{t}=\left(r_{t1},\,...\,,\,r_{tN}\right)^{\prime},\ t=1,\,,2,\,\cdots,\,T$
\end_inset

 are multivariate normal.
 The proof, however, is fairly complex and is typically covered only in
 multivariate statistics courses.
 Maximum–likelihood estimators for the case of non–normal multivariate elliptica
l distributions are discussed in 
