\begin_layout Section
Useful Inequalities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Markov's Inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is any non–negative random variable (
\begin_inset Formula $X\geqslant0$
\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a positive constant, then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(X\geqslant a)\leqslant\dfrac{\mathrm{E}\left[X\right]}{a},\,a>0.\label{eq: MarkovInequality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Moment Bound
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Markov's Inequality is easily extended to higher moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is any non–negative random variable, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are positive constants, then:.

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(X\geqslant a)\leqslant\dfrac{\mathrm{E}\left[X^{r}\right]}{a^{r}},\ a,\,r>0.\label{eq: MomentBound1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In particular,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(X\geqslant a)\leqslant\underset{r>0}{\inf}\dfrac{\mathrm{E}\left[X^{r}\right]}{a^{r}},\ a>0.\label{eq: MomentBound2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: MomentBound2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is known as the 
\emph on
Moment Bound
\emph default
, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "PhilipsNelson1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that the moment bound is tighter than Chernoff's Bound for positive
 tail probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Chebyshev's Inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\mathrm{E}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=\mathrm{E}\left[(X-\mu)^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is any positive constant, then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(\left|X-\mu\right|\geqslant b\right)\leqslant\dfrac{\sigma^{2}}{b^{2}},\ b>0.\label{eq: ChebyshevInequalityAppB}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Chernoff's Bound
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chernoff's Bound is the tightest general purpose inequality that applies
 to random variables whose domain is the entire real line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P(X\geqslant a) & \leqslant\underset{\theta>0}{\inf}\dfrac{\mathrm{E}(\exp\left(\theta X\right))}{\exp\left(\theta a\right)}\label{eq: ChernoffsBound1}\\
P(X\leqslant a) & \leqslant\underset{\theta<0}{\inf}\dfrac{\mathrm{E}(\exp\left(\theta X\right))}{\exp\left(\theta a\right)}.\label{eq:ChernoffsBound2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Jensen's Inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probabilistic version of Jensen's inequality for the case of a convex
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a generalization of the statement that the secant line of a function
 lies below the function.
 Specifically, if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a random variable with expected value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{E}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a convex function, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(\mathrm{E}\left[X\right]\right)\leqslant\mathrm{E}\left[g(X)\right].\label{eq: JensenInequalityConvexFnc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a strictly convex function, then Jensen's inequality is strict:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(\mathrm{E}\left[X\right]\right)<\mathrm{E}\left[g(X)\right].\label{eq: JensenInequalityStrictlyConvexFnc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a concave and strictly concave functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, the above inequalities are reversed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Limit Theorems for Random Variables and Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section discusses key limit theorems of sequences of random variables
 and distribution functions that play a central role in the large sample
 asymptotic theory of parameter estimators.
 For further background on such asymptotics, the document 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Notes for a graduate level course in asymptotics for statisticians
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by Professor David R.
 Hunter (available at 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://sites.math.rutgers.edu/~sg1108/asymp1.pdf
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is highly recommended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Random Variables Convergence
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Random-Variables-Convergence"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Convergence in Probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An infinite sequence of random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\,X_{2,}\cdots$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
converges in probability
\emph default
 to a random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 the following limit condition holds
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{n\rightarrow\infty}{\lim}P\left(|X_{n}\,-\,X|<\epsilon\right)=1,\label{eq: convInProbDef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and in that case we write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{n}\overset{p}{\rightarrow}X.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Sometimes 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 will be a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $X=c$
\end_inset

, and frequently the random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 are parameter estimates 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}=\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
Weak Law of Large Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\,X_{2,}\cdots$
\end_inset

 are independent and identically distributed with finite mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\mathrm{E}(X_{1})$
\end_inset

, then the sample mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}_{n}=\dfrac{1}{n}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 converges in probability to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{X}_{n}\overset{p}{\rightarrow}\mu.\label{eq: WLLN}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The proof of the result as stated is involved.
 But a proof under the assumption that the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 have finite variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, which is often a reasonable assumption, is an easy consequence of Chebychev's
 inequality.

\series bold
 
\series default
Additionally, it is not hard to show that for i.i.d.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 with finite variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{-1}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}(X_{i}\,-\,\mu)^{2}$
\end_inset

 converges in probability to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convergence in Distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the infinite sequence of random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\,X_{2},\,\cdots$
\end_inset

 have cumulative distribution functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}(x),\,F_{2}(x),\cdots,$
\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 have cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be the set of points of continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\,X_{2,}\,\cdots$
\end_inset

 is said to 
\emph on
converge in distribution
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{n\,\rightarrow\,\infty}{lim}F_{n}(x)=F(x),\,x\in C\label{eq: convInDist}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and one writes this as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{n}\overset{d}{\rightarrow}X\quad\mathrm{or}\quad X_{n}\overset{d}{\rightarrow}F.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

NOTE: For our purposes in this book the reader will only need the above
 two types of convergence of random variables.
 However, there are other modes of convergence of random variables, e.g.,
 convergence almost surely and convergence in mean, and the interested reader
 can find a good discussion of these in the Hunter reference given at the
 beginning of this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Slutsky's Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\,X_{2}\cdots$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1},\,Y_{2}\cdots$
\end_inset

 are infinite sequences of random variables such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}\overset{d}{\rightarrow}X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{n}\overset{p}{\rightarrow}c$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a constant, then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{n}\,+\,Y_{n}\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,X\,+\,c,\qquad X_{n}Y_{n}\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,cX\qquad X_{n}/Y_{n}\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,X/c,\:\mathrm{provided}\,c\ne0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Central Limit Theorem (CLT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},\,X_{2,}\,\cdots$
\end_inset

 be an infinite sequence of independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.)
 random variables with finite mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, finite variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the sample mean of the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 for a sample of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 There exist a number of sophisticated 
\emph on
central limit theorems
\emph default
 (CLTs) asserting the asymptotic normality of the sample mean, the simplest
 of which is the following classical CLT:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}\left(\overline{X}_{n}\,-\,\mu\right)\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,N\left(0,\,\sigma^{2}\right)\quad\mathrm{or}\quad\sqrt{n}\left(\overline{X}_{n}\,-\,\mu\right)\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,Y\label{eq: CLTv1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is normally distributed with mean zero and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, this CLT can be stated as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}\,\dfrac{\overline{X}\,-\,\mu}{\sigma}\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,N\left(0,\,1\right).\label{eq: CLTv2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimator Asymptotic Results and Their Use
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Consistent Estimators
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: estConsistent"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\emph on
consistent
\emph default
 estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is one that 
\emph on
converges in probability
\emph default
 to the true but unknown parameter value 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 as the sample size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity, and we write this property of an estimator as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\theta}_{n}\,\stackrel{p}{\rightarrow}\,\theta.\label{eq: convInProb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We provide a precise mathematical definition of convergence in probability
 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Random-Variables-Convergence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, but a verbal description of this property is as follows: as the sample
 size tends to infinity, the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\theta\right|$
\end_inset

 is smaller than any specified positive amount converges to 1.

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most estimators commonly used in practice are consistent under standard
 assumptions.
 For example, the sample mean is a consistent estimator of the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, the sample variance estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are both consistent estimators of the variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, and the sample standard deviation estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a consistent estimator of the standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimator Asymptotic Variance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec: estAsympVariance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the sample mean
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{r}_{n}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}r_{t}
\]

\end_inset

based on on uncorrelated returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t},\:t=1,\,2,\,\ldots\,,\,n$
\end_inset

 with a common mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and common variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 When the context is clear we will drop the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{r}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known that the finite sample variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{r}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{n}\left(\overline{r}\right)=\mathrm{var}(\overline{r})=\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}.
\]

\end_inset

and so the variance of the sample mean goes to zero at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most well–known estimators have a variance that converges to zero at a rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n$
\end_inset

 under standard assumptions.
 For example, the sample median, sample covariance, sample correlation coefficie
nt, and regression coefficient estimators, among many others, have variances
 that decrease at a rate 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n$
\end_inset

.
 For any such estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

, one can obtain an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

asymptotic variance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by applying a multiplicative factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 to the estimator in an appropriate manner.
 For example, in the case of the sample mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{r}_{n}$
\end_inset

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left(\sqrt{n}\,\overline{r}_{n}\right)=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 for every sample size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If an estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a consistent estimator of a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, then under certain standard conditions satisfied by most estimators encountere
d in practice, the distribution of the standardized estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 converges in distribution to a normal distribution that has mean zero and
 an asymptotic variance 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\theta;\,\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

, which is written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\theta\right)\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,N\left(0,\,V\left(\theta;\,\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)\right).\label{eq: sqrtnStandardizedEstimator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The argument 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\theta;\,\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 reflects that fact that the asymptotic variance depends on the choice of
 estimator, and when the context makes it clear which estimator is being
 considered, the asymptotic variance is written more simply as 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Asymptotic Variance of the Sample Variance Estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If i.i.d.
 returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 have a finite fourth moment, then it turns out that the asymptotic variance
 of the sample variance estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}\left(r_{i}\,-\,\bar{r}_{n}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V(\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2})=\mathrm{var}\left[\left(r_{1}\,-\,\mu\right)^{2}\right]=\mu_{4}\,-\,\sigma^{4}\label{eq: asympVarianceSampleVariance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{4}=\mathrm{E}\left[(r\,-\,\mu)^{4}\right]$
\end_inset

 is the fourth central moment.
 A proof of the this result is as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\mathrm{var}\left(r_{1}\,-\,\mu\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

, and note that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a & =\mathrm{E}\left[(r_{1}\,-\,\mu)^{4}\right]\,-\,\mathrm{E}^{2}\left[(r_{1}\,-\,\mu)^{2}\right]\\
 & =\mu_{4}\,-\,\sigma^{4}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 from both 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{r}$
\end_inset

 does not change the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}-\bar{r}$
\end_inset

, we can assume the mean of the 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 Consequently
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}\left(r_{i}\,-\,\bar{r}_{n}\right)^{2} & =\frac{1}{n}\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}r_{i}^{2}\,-\,\frac{2}{n}\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}r_{i}\bar{r}_{n}\,+\,\bar{r}_{n}^{2}\\
 & =\frac{1}{n}\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}r_{i}^{2}\,-\,\bar{r}_{n}^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and recalling that the mean of the 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is zero, we have.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{2}\,-\,\sigma^{2}\right)=\sqrt{n}\left(\frac{1}{n}\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}r_{i}^{2}\,-\,\sigma^{2}\right)\,-\,\sqrt{n}\,\bar{r}_{n}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows from the CLT that the first term on the right converges in distributi
on to a 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,\,a)$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 Furthermore, the second term can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{r}_{n}\,\sqrt{n}\,\bar{r}_{n}$
\end_inset

, and, by the CLT, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}\,\bar{r}_{n}\stackrel{d}{\rightarrow}Z$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,1)$
\end_inset

 random variable, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{r}_{n}$
\end_inset

 converges in probability to 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0$
\end_inset

.
 By Slutsky's Theorem the right hand side of the above equation converges
 to a 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,\,a)$
\end_inset

 distribution.

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Example
Asymptotic Variance of a Location M–Estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here we provide a heuristic derivation of the asymptotic normality and correspon
ding asymptotic variance of a location M–estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{n}=\hat{\mu}_{n}(x_{1},\,x_{2},\,\cdots,\,x_{n})$
\end_inset

, defined as a solution of the equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}\psi(x_{i}-\hat{\mu}_{n})=0\label{eq: MestEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(r)$
\end_inset

 is a continuous odd function, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(-x)=-\psi(x).$
\end_inset

 It is assumed that the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i},\ i=1,\,2,\,\cdots,\,n$
\end_inset

 are independent and identically distributed with distribution function
 
\begin_inset Formula $F=F(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}=\mu_{0}(F)$
\end_inset

 as the solution, assumed to be unique, of the equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{F}\psi(r-\mu_{0})=0.\label{eq: asympMestEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Under reasonable assumptions, it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a consistent estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 See for example Section 2.10.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), whose derivation of asymptotic normality we follow here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
*** Add derivation here ***
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Delta Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first discuss the univariate delta method that allows one to obtain the
 asymptotic variance of a nonlinear transformation of an estimator, a leading
 example of which is obtaining the asymptotic variance of a sample volatility
 estimator from the asymptotic variance of a sample variance estimator.
 We then discuss the bivariate delta method that that allows one to obtain
 the asymptotic variance of a performance estimator that is the ratio of
 two estimators based on the same set of returns, e.g., the Sharpe ratio and
 Sortino ratio, from the asymptotic 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 covariance matrix of the individual estimators for the numerator and denominato
r.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Univariate Delta Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a formula 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\theta)=V(\theta;\,\hat{\theta}_{n})$
\end_inset

 for the asymptotic variance of a consistent estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

, and want to find the variance 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\theta;\,g\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 of a nonlinear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

, where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)$
\end_inset

 has a continuous first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\prime}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the Mean Value Theorem 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(see Appendix B)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)=g(\theta)\,+\,g^{\prime}(\theta^{*})\,\cdot\,\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\theta\right),\ \mathrm{where}\:\theta^{*}\:\mathrm{lies}\ \mathrm{between}\ \theta\ \mathrm{and}\ \hat{\theta}_{n}.\,\label{eq:UnivariateDeltaStep1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}\left(g\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)\,-\,g(\theta)\right)=g^{\prime}(\theta^{*})\,\cdot\,\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\,-\,\theta\right),\ \mathrm{with}\:\theta^{*}\ \mathrm{between}\ \theta\ \mathrm{and}\ \hat{\theta}_{n}.\label{eq:UnivariateDeltaStep2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Taking the limit on the right hand side as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\,\rightarrow\,\infty$
\end_inset

, the consistency of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{*}\,\stackrel{p}{\rightarrow}\,\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\theta^{*})\,\stackrel{p}{\rightarrow}\,g(\theta)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\,\rightarrow\,\infty$
\end_inset

, and so the right hand side converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\prime}(\theta)\,\cdot\,Y$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 has mean zero and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by Slutsky's Theorem, the right hand side converges to a random variable
 with mean zero and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[g^{\prime}(\theta)\right]^{2}\,\cdot\,V(\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the asymptotic variance of the left hand side above is:
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(\theta;\,g\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)\right)=\left[g^{\prime}(\theta)\right]^{2}V(\theta).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Volatility Estimator Asymptotic Variance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Since volatility is related to variance through the square root transformation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\sqrt{\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

, the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $g(t)=t^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\prime}(t)=t^{-1/2}/2$
\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\theta=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[g^{\prime}(\theta)\right]^{2}=\nicefrac{1}{\,4\,\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and use of the formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: asympVarianceSampleVariance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for the asymptotic variance of the sample variance gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V(\sigma;\,\hat{\sigma}_{n})=\dfrac{\mu_{4}\,-\,\sigma^{4}}{4\sigma^{2}}.\label{eq: asympVarianceVolEst}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Bivariate Delta Method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performance estimators such as the Sharpe ratio, the Sortino ratio, and
 the Information ratio, are ratios of two estimators, and for the purpose
 of the discussion here, it is assumed that both estimators use the same
 set of i.i.d.
 returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the Sharpe ratio estimator is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\mathrm{SR}}=\dfrac{\hat{\mu}_{e}}{\hat{\sigma}}=\dfrac{\hat{\mu}\,-\,r_{f}}{\hat{\sigma}}\label{eq: SRestimator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the sample mean, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the sample variance, of the set of returns.
 For purposes of the discussion here, it is assumed that the 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 are independent and identically distributed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A performance ratio estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\mathrm{PR}}$
\end_inset

 in general has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{\mathrm{PR}}=\dfrac{\hat{\theta}_{1}}{\hat{\theta}_{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two estimators based on the same set of returns.
 The asymptotic variance of such an estimator can be computed using the
 following bivariate delta method, which is an extension of the univariate
 delta method in the previous sub–section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\butheta=(\theta_{1},\,\theta_{2})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\butheta)=g(\theta_{1},\,\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 be a scalar–valued transformation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\butheta$
\end_inset

.
 Then given a bivariate estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\butheta}=(\hat{\theta}_{1},\,\hat{\theta}_{2})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, one obtains the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{g(\butheta)}=g(\hat{\theta}_{1},\,\hat{\theta}_{2})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\butheta)$
\end_inset

.
 For example, in the case of the Sharpe ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(\butheta)=\dfrac{\theta_{1}}{\sqrt{\theta_{2}}}\quad\mathrm{with}\quad\theta_{1}=\mu_{e},\:\theta_{2}=\sigma^{2}.\label{eq: gThetaSharpeRatio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Taylor series expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{g(\butheta)}$
\end_inset

 about the true value 
\begin_inset Formula $\butheta$
\end_inset

 gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{g(\butheta)}=g(\butheta)\,+\,\dfrac{\partial g(\butheta)}{\partial\theta_{1}}\left(\hat{\theta}_{1}\,-\,\theta_{1}\right)\,+\,\dfrac{\partial g(\butheta)}{\partial\theta_{2}}\left(\hat{\theta}_{2}\,-\,\theta_{2}\right)\,+\,Rem_{n}
\]

\end_inset

where the estimates are based on i.i.d.
 returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n}$
\end_inset

, and the remainder 
\begin_inset Formula $Rem_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be shown to go to zero faster than 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 under standard conditions.
 The asymptotic variance 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\hat{g}}=V_{\hat{g}}(\butheta)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{g(\butheta)}$
\end_inset

 is the limiting asymptotic variance of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{n}\,\cdot\,\left(\widehat{g(\butheta)}\,-\,g(\butheta)\right)=\dfrac{\partial g(\butheta)}{\partial\theta_{1}}\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\theta}_{1}\,-\,\theta_{1}\right)\,+\,\dfrac{\partial g(\butheta)}{\partial\theta_{2}}\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\theta}_{2}\,-\,\theta_{2}\right)\,+\,\sqrt{n}\,\cdot\,Rem_{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming the usual asymptotic joint normality of the estimates 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{2}$
\end_inset

, and noting that the remainder term goes to zero asymptotically, the asymptotic
 variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{g(\butheta)}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{\hat{g}}=\nabla g(\butheta)^{\prime}\,\mathbf{V}_{\butheta}\,\nabla g(\butheta)\label{eq: ghatVariance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}_{\butheta}$
\end_inset

 is the asymptotic covariance matrix of the estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\butheta}=(\hat{\theta}_{1},\,\hat{\theta}_{2})^{\prime}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{V}_{\butheta}=\left(\begin{array}{ll}
\mathrm{var}_{\infty}(\hat{\theta}_{1}) & \ \mathrm{cov}_{\infty}(\hat{\theta}_{1},\,\hat{\theta}_{2})\\
\mathrm{cov}_{\infty}(\hat{\theta}_{1},\,\hat{\theta}_{2}) & \ \mathrm{var}_{\infty}(\hat{\theta}_{2})
\end{array}\right).\label{eq: VthetaCovMat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For estimators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{2}$
\end_inset

 that are sums of non–linear functions of i.i.d.
 returns, the above asymptotic variances and covariances can be computed
 from a single term of each of the two summations.
 This is the case in the following example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The Sharpe Ratio Asymptotic Variance Using the Bivariate Delta Method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Sharpe ratio we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{1}=\bar{r}\,-\,r_{f}=\dfrac{1}{n}\,\sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}r_{i}\,-\,r_{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{2}=\dfrac{1}{n}\,\sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}(r_{i}\,-\,\bar{r})^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The asymptotic variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, and from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: asympVarianceSampleVariance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we know that the asymptotic variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{4}\,-\,\sigma^{4}$
\end_inset

.
 The asymptotic covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is easily shown to be 
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{3}=\mathrm{E}\left[(r_{1}\,-\,\mu)^{3}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{V}_{\butheta}=\left(\begin{array}{ll}
\sigma^{2} & \ \mu_{3}\\
\mu_{3} & \ \mu_{4}\,-\,\sigma^{4}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and since for the Sharpe ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\butheta)$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: gThetaSharpeRatio"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, its gradient is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla g(\butheta)=\left(\dfrac{1}{\sigma},\,-\dfrac{\mu_{e}}{2\,\sigma^{3}}\right)^{\prime}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging the above two expressions into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: ghatVariance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows 
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged
that the asymptotic variance of the Sharpe ratio is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
V_{\widehat{SR}} & =1\,-\,K_{3}\,\cdot\,SR\,+\,\dfrac{K_{4}\,+\,2}{4}\,{SR}^{2}\label{eq: asympVarianceSR}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{3}=\mu_{3}/\sigma^{3}$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient of skewness, and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}=\mu_{4}/\sigma^{4}\,-\,3$
\end_inset

 is excess kurtosis.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mertens2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

derived this result in terms of the coefficient of kurtosis 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{4}$
\end_inset

, rather than the coefficient of excess kurtosis 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}$
\end_inset

, and so his formula with the 
\begin_inset Formula ${SR}^{2}$
\end_inset

 terms combined, has 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{4}+2$
\end_inset

 replaced with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{3}-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In the special case of normally distributed returns, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{3}=K_{4}=0$
\end_inset

, the above expression reduces to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{var}_{\infty}\left({\mathrm{SR}}_{n}\right)=1\,+\,\dfrac{1}{2}{\mathrm{SR}}^{2}\label{eq:asympVarianceSRnormalReturnsAppendixB}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the version derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lo2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimator Standard Errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exact standard errors of estimators exist only in very special cases such
 as the sample mean, least–squares regression estimators and the unbiased
 sample variance estimator, and under an assumption of normality.
 However, one may use an estimator's asymptotic variance to compute an approxima
te standard error (SE) of the estimator, and this is one of the most important
 uses of estimator asymptotic variance expressions.
 We discuss this use in the context of an estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 of a true but unknown scalar parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, based on an i.i.d.
 sample of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Standard Errors Based on Asymptotic Variance Formulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to compute a SE for an estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

, the first step is to determine the formula for the asymptotic variance
 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\theta\right)=V\left(\theta;\,\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If the value of the parameter value 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 were known, then the formula for an approximate SE of an estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 would be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SE\left(\hat{\theta}_{n};\,\theta\right)\approx\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}V^{1/2}(\theta).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

But since the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is not known, we can replace the unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 with its estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the following estimate of the approximate SE:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SE\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)\approx\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}V^{1/2}(\hat{\theta}_{n}).\label{eq: afsSE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\emph on
Comment
\emph default
: We typically use a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 symbol over parameter estimates, and if we followed that convention we
 would use 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{SE}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But for sake of simplicity of notation we do not do so, and it will be
 understood that 
\begin_inset Formula $SE\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an estimate of a standard error, that we refer to simply as the computed
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard error
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Example 1.1.

\emph default
 Volatility Estimator Standard Error
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of the volatility estimator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{vol,n}$
\end_inset

 the SE is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SE\left(\hat{\sigma}_{vol,\,n}\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\left(\dfrac{\hat{\mu}_{4,\,n}\,-\,\hat{\sigma}_{vol,\,n}^{4}}{4\hat{\sigma}_{vol,\,n}^{2}}\right)^{1/2},\quad\mathrm{where}\quad\hat{\mu}_{4,\,n}=\frac{1}{n}\,\sum_{t\,=\,1}^{n}\left(r_{t}\,-\,\overline{r}\right)^{4}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fisher Information and MLE Asymptotic Optimality
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: Fisher Info & MLE Optimality"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})$
\end_inset

 are i.i.d.
 random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})$
\end_inset

 with pdf 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\mathbf{r};\,\theta)$
\end_inset

.
 Then with 
\begin_inset Formula $l(\theta;\,\mathbf{r})=\ln f(\mathbf{r};\,\theta)$
\end_inset

 the natural log of the pdf, the 
\emph on
Fisher Information
\emph default
 for estimating the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I(\theta)=\mathrm{E}\left[\left(\dfrac{\partial l(\theta;\,r)}{\partial\theta}\right)^{2}\right].\label{eq: FisherInfo}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If z
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{mle,\,n}=\hat{\theta}_{mle,\,n}(r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence of consistent MLEs of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, then it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{mle,\,n}$
\end_inset

 is asymptotically normal with asymptotic variance 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{-1}(\theta)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}\left(\hat{\theta}_{mle,\,n}\,-\,\theta\right)\,\overset{d}{\rightarrow}\,N\left(0,\,I^{-1}(\theta)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, any other consistent estimator, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{n}$
\end_inset

, has an asymptotic variance 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\hat{\theta}_{n};\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the information inequality
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V\left(\hat{\theta}_{n};\,\theta\right)\geqslant I^{-1}(\theta).\label{eq: asympInfoInequality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The above results reflect the asymptotic optimality of an MLE 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}_{mle,\,n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Generalized Inverse of Distribution Functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Generalized-Inverse-of Distribution Function"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any distribution function that has one or more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spots, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=c$
\end_inset

 for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 on some interval 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

, the inverse function 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}(c)$
\end_inset

 does not exist.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The notation 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 means all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a<x<b$
\end_inset

, and the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 means all numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a<x\leqslant b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An empirical distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}(r)$
\end_inset

 is an extreme version of this in that it is a pure step function consisting
 only of flat spots with values 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=i/n,i=1,\,2,\,\cdots\,,\,n$
\end_inset

.
 One can handle the presence of flat spots in a distribution function through
 use of the following generalized inverse function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F^{\leftarrow}(p)=inf\left\{ r:\,p\leqslant F(r)\right\} ,\,0<p\leqslant1.\label{eq: ginverseDF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and takes on each of those values for many values of the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.

\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Application to Empirical Distribution Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the EDF 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 of a sample 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},\,r_{2},\,\cdots\,,\,r_{n}$
\end_inset

 that has no ties, the ordered data satisfy the strict inequalities 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(1)}\,<\,r_{(2)}\,<\,\cdots\,<\,r_{(n)}$
\end_inset

, and the generalized inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{n}^{\leftarrow}(p)=r_{(i)},\,p\in\left((i\,-\,1)\,/\,n,\ i\,/\,n\right],\,i=1,\,2,\,\cdots\,,\,n.\label{eq: ginverseEDF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So for example, 
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula $F_{4}^{-1}(p)=r_{(2)}\,\forall p\in\left(1/4,\,1/2\right]$
\end_inset

, which may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{4}^{-1}(p)=r_{(2)}\,\forall\,4p\in\left(1,\,2\right]$
\end_inset

.
 What this reveals is that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

–quantile of an EDF for a returns sample of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is:
\change_deleted 267031586 1693580207
 
\change_unchanged

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{F_{n}}(p)=F_{n}^{\leftarrow}(p)=r_{(\left\lceil np\right\rceil )}.
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lceil x\right\rceil $
\end_inset

 is defined as the smallest integer greater than or equal to 
