\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
Generalized Inverse of Distribution Functions and an EDF Quantiles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For any distribution function that has one or more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spots, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=c$
\end_inset

 for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 on some interval 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(a,b)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

, the inverse function 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{-1}(c)$
\end_inset

 does not exist.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The notation 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 means all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $a<x<b$
\end_inset

, and the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,b\right]$
\end_inset

 means all numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a<x\leqslant b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An empirical distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}(r)$
\end_inset

 is an extreme version of this in that it is a pure step function consisting
 only of flat spots with values 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=i/n,i=1,2,\cdots,n$
\end_inset

.
 One can handle the presence of flat spots in a distribution function through
 use of the following generalized (left) inverse function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F^{\leftarrow}(p)=inf\left\{ r:p\leqslant F(r)\right\} ,\,0<p\leqslant1.\label{eq: ginverseDF-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and takes on each of those values for many values of the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the EDF 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 of a sample 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1},r_{2},\cdots,r_{n}$
\end_inset

 that has no ties, the ordered data have the strict inequalities 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{(1)}<r_{(2)}<\cdots<r_{(n)}$
\end_inset

 and the generalized inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{n}^{\leftarrow}(p)=r_{(i)},\,p\in\left((i-1)\thinspace/\thinspace n,\ i\thinspace/\thinspace n\right],\,i=1,\thinspace2,\cdots,\thinspace n.\label{eq: ginverseEDF-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
So for example in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: edfRet4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{4}^{-1}(p)=r_{(2)}\,\forall p\in\left(1/4,\ 1/2\right]$
\end_inset

, which may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{4}^{-1}(p)=r_{(2)}\,\forall\,4p\in\left(1,\ 2\right]$
\end_inset

.
 What this reveals is that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

-quantile of an EDF for a returns sample of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{F_{n}}(p)=F_{n}^{\leftarrow}(p)=r_{(\left\lceil np\right\rceil )}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\lceil x\right\rceil $
\end_inset

 is defined as the smallest integer greater or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for example when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=50$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.01$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{F_{50}}(0.01)=r_{(\left\lceil 0.5\right\rceil )}=r_{(1)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

